1.2 Research summary
Design ideas that can be used in existing tools include:
1.	Hierarchical functional design: Focusing on the core needs of different user groups, giving priority to coverage breadth for general tools and in-depth local services for vertical tools, which provides a reference for the functional focus of this project, which can focus on the core route planning functions for the basic needs of students/local commuting. 
2.	Multi-dimensional route preferences: Mainstream tools allow users to filter and sort routes according to different travel preferences (fastest/cheapest/least transfers), which is completely in line with the needs of this project, and can learn from its design idea of using different cost dimensions as the basis for sorting. 
3.	Clear transfer guidance: Mature tools will provide detailed transfer details to help users reduce the cognitive burden of transfers, which can be used as a reference in the route output of this project, and clearly mark the transfer points and road section information for users. 
At the same time, there are some design issues with existing tools:
1.	Contradiction in functional trade-offs: Most tools cannot take into account the breadth of coverage and the depth of local services, the local details of general tools are insufficient, and the functions of vertical tools are too limited, resulting in users often needing to switch multiple apps to complete the itinerary planning. 
2.	Offline experience is uneven: The offline function of most tools can only meet basic queries and cannot support complete offline route planning, but this project is designed based on static data, which can naturally support complete offline use, which can make up for this experience shortcoming. 

2. Definition of the problem framework
2.1 Core Entity Definitions
To model the commuting problem as a computational problem, this project clearly defines the core entities:
1.	Stops: nodes in the public transportation network, which are the locations of passengers getting on and off the bus, each station has a unique identity and name, which can be shared by different transportation lines, and is the basic node of route planning. 
2.	Segments: Edges in the public transportation network, connecting two adjacent stations, representing one-way traffic sections between two stations, belonging to a specific traffic line, and being the basic unit of traffic in the network. 
3.	Cost: The fare that passengers need to pay for this section of the journey, in Hong Kong dollars, is used to calculate the total fare of the entire trip and is the core calculation basis for the "cheapest" preference. 
4.	Duration: The time it takes for passengers to pass through this section, in minutes, is a static preset travel time used to calculate the total time spent on the entire trip, and is the core calculation basis for the "fastest" preference. 
5.	Journey: A complete travel plan from the starting point to the end station, consisting of a series of orderly road sections, including transfer points, total cost, total duration, total number of road sections, number of transfers and other complete travel information. 
6.	Preference Mode: The route sorting based on the user's choice, this project supports three core modes:
￮	Cheapest: Prioritize the route with the lowest total fare based on the total cost of the trip
￮	Fastest: Based on the total duration of the trip, the route with the shortest total time is recommended first
￮	Minimum road section: Based on the total number of road sections of the itinerary (corresponding to the number of transfers), the route with the least transfer is recommended first, reducing the transfer burden of users
2.2 Input and output definitions
Enter the definition
The inputs received by the program fall into two categories:
1.	Network initialization input: Supports reading static data of the transportation network, including all station information and road section information, from the specified text file, completes the initialization of the transportation network, and supports input verification to ensure that the data format is legal. 
2.	User query input:
￮	Starting point: the user's departure station, supported by the station name or unique identifier, the program verifies that the stop exists in the current transportation network
￮	Endpoint: The user's destination site, which also supports the site name or unique identifier, and the program verifies the validity of the site
￮	Preferred Selection: The route sorting preference selected by the user, with the value of the cheapest/fastest/least section, the program verifies whether the input preference is a supported type
Output definition
The output of the program is the user's route query results, including:
1.	Sorted Candidate Route List: All eligible candidate trips are sorted from highest to lowest priority according to the user's preferred preferences, and the routes that best meet the user's needs are prioritized. 
2.	Details of individual routes:
￮	Complete Stop Sequence: All stops passed in order from start to finish
￮	Total Cost: The total fare for the entire route
￮	Total Duration: The total time spent on the entire route
￮	Road section and transfer information: the total number of sections of the route, as well as the corresponding number of transfers and transfer stops,
 the program supports file output, and the query results can be saved to the specified text file for users to keep and view. 
2.3 Delineation of functional boundaries
In order to focus on core computational thinking and data model design, this project clearly delineates the functional boundaries, and the following functions will not be implemented in this program:
1.	It does not provide a real-time map visualization interface, only supports text interactive information display, and does not provide graphical map or route visualization.
2.	Real-time traffic data is not supported, and the duration and fare of all road sections are static data, regardless of real-time congestion, delays, temporary diversions and other dynamic changes.
3.	It does not support cross-city route planning, but only supports route query of public transportation networks within a single city.
4.	It does not support independent walking route planning, and only the walking between stations is used as an auxiliary part of the transfer, and the walking section is not modeled separately.
5.	Dynamic estimated time of arrival (ETA) calculations are not supported, and all durations are static presets and are not dynamically adjusted based on the current time.
6.	Accessibility-related route filtering is not supported, and accessibility-related information is not included in the simplified model of this project.
7.	It does not support complex multi-destination route planning, and only supports single-point-to-single-point start-end route query.
8.	It does not support ticketing and payment-related functions, only provides fare estimate information, and does not support actual ticket purchase and payment operations.
9.	It does not support personalized data storage, and cannot save personalized information such as frequently used routes and historical queries.
10.	Cross-device synchronization is not supported, and all data is only effective when the local program is running.

